<article>
    <h1>Op&#xAD;tions after&#xD;&#xA;O lev&#xAD;els</h1>
    <h2>With the re&#xAD;lease of the O-level ex&#xAD;am&#xAD;i&#xAD;na&#xAD;tion re&#xAD;sults to&#xAD;day, par&#xAD;ents and stu&#xAD;dents will need to de&#xAD;cide which post-sec&#xAD;ondary route to take.&#xD;&#xA;The Straits Times gets your ques&#xAD;tions about ju&#xAD;nior col&#xAD;leges and poly&#xAD;tech&#xAD;nics an&#xAD;swered by ex&#xAD;perts Ju&#xAD;nior col&#xAD;lege: In&#xAD;ten</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20210111/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2021-01-11"><time>2021-01-11</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline">Amelia Teng&#xD;&#xA;Ed&#xAD;u&#xAD;ca&#xAD;tion Cor&#xAD;re&#xAD;spon&#xAD;dent</span>
    </section>

    <p>The Straits Times speaks to Mrs Wong-Cheang Mei Heng, prin­ci­pal of Eunoia Ju­nior Col­lege (EJC), to un­der­stand the JC track.</p>
    <p>Why opt for JC?</p>
    <p>A JC ed­u­ca­tion of­fers stu­dents a strong aca­demic foun­da­tion, both in terms of breadth and depth of learn­ing, through a range of cour­ses that they can choose from.</p>
    <p>The A-level cur­ricu­lum in a JC suits stu­dents who want to in­ves­ti­gate the un­der­ly­ing con­cepts be­hind real-world phe­nom­ena, con­vey their un­der­stand­ing ac­cu­rately and ex­press their own ideas in a per­sonal voice.</p>
    <p>Two schools – St Joseph’s In­sti­tu­tion and An­glo-Chi­nese School (In­de­pen­dent) – of­fer the In­ter­na­tional Bac­calau­re­ate Di­ploma Pro­gramme (IBDP) in­stead of the A lev­els.</p>
    <p>What is the learn­ing style of stu­dents in JC?</p>
    <p>JC stu­dents tend di­rected learn­ers.</p>
    <p>While many JCs adopt a lec­ture­tu­to­rial sys­tem, there is more col­lab­o­ra­tive learn­ing to­day – group dis­cus­sions and pre­sen­ta­tions are com­mon across all sub­jects.</p>
    <p>Pro­ject Work, which JC stu­dents take in their first year, in­cor­po­rates re­search, col­lab­o­ra­tion, re­port writ­ing and oral pre­sen­ta­tions into its cur­ricu­lum – the same skills learnt in many poly­tech­nic cour­ses.</p>
    <p>Hands-on learn­ing in the form of prac­ti­cals, field work and per­for­mance work­shops takes place across the sub­jects.</p>
    <p>JC stu­dents ap­ply their knowl­edge through clear and ac­cu­rate writ­ing, with writ­ten ex­am­i­na­tions be­ing the pri­mary mode of as­sess­ment for most A-level sub­jects. to be self</p>
    <p>What is the aca­demic work­load? The con­trast­ing sub­ject re­quire­ment and the mix of sub­jects at Higher 1, 2 and 3 (H1, H2 and H3) lev­els pro­vide stu­dents a wide range of op­tions in the sci­ence and arts streams. Stu­dents can de­ter­mine sub­ject com­bi­na­tions based on their in­ter­ests and fu­ture ed­u­ca­tional pur­suits.</p>
    <p>The JC jour­ney is of­ten de­scribed as an en­riched yet short and in­ten­sive one, with the A-level (or IBDP) ex­am­i­na­tion as­sess­ing stu­dents’ learn­ing at the end of two years.</p>
    <p>Stu­dents who pre­fer more op­por­tu­ni­ties for hands-on learn­ing and bite-size and cu­mu­la­tive as­sess­ment may en­joy the poly­tech­nic sys­tem more.</p>
    <p>How rig­or­ous is the JC cur­ricu­lum?</p>
    <p>Stu­dents learn to think crit­i­cally as well as eval­u­ate, syn­the­sise and ap­ply what they have learnt to demon­strate their learn­ing.</p>
    <p>H3-level sub­jects will ex­cite stu­dents who are keen to ex­plore a par­tic­u­lar dis­ci­pline in even greater depth. They can also take on in­de­pen­dent re­search pa­pers, at­tend univer­sity-level mod­ules and be men­tored by univer­sity pro­fes­sors.</p>
    <p>Do JCs pre­pare stu­dents bet­ter for univer­sity?</p>
    <p>The as­sump­tion that the JC path­way is more likely to lead to univer­sity than the poly­tech­nic route is no longer true. Both JC and poly­tech­nic stu­dents are well-equipped with the knowl­edge and skills to thrive in their next stage of learn­ing and fu­ture ca­reers.</p>
    <p>A JC ed­u­ca­tion of­fers a more holis­tic un­der­stand­ing of dif­fer­ent do­mains and dis­ci­plines.</p>
    <p>As uni­ver­si­ties move to­wards greater in­ter­dis­ci­plinar­ity, the JC cur­ricu­lum and en­rich­ment pro­grammes seek to fur­ther ex­pose stu­dents to in­ter­dis­ci­pli­nary and mul­ti­dis­ci­plinary learn­ing and their ap­pli­ca­tions to real-world problems.</p>
    <p>For in­stance, EJC of­fers tal­ent de­vel­op­ment pro­grammes that en­cour­age stu­dents to ex­plore public pol­icy and ad­vo­cacy, fu­tures method­olo­gies and eth­i­cal is­sues in the life sciences.</p>
    <p>In ad­di­tion, teach­ers and school lead­ers in JCs mon­i­tor the univer­sity land­scape and guide stu­dents to se­lect sub­jects that pre­pare them for cour­ses they are keen on.</p>
    <p>Stu­dents will also be equipped with skills like re­search that will help them to thrive in uni­ver­si­ties.</p>

